						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Biotechnology/Related-developments/BASF-partners-with-leading-research-institutes-to-reduce-crop-loss-from-striga-weed-in-Africa" title="BASF partners with leading research institutes to reduce crop loss from striga weed in Africa" alt="link">BASF partners with leading research institutes to reduce crop loss from striga weed in Africa</a></h2>

	
					<p>Badische Anilin- und Soda-Fabrik (BASF) and the International Institute of Tropical Agriculture (IITA), the African Agricultural Technology Foundation (AATF), and the International Maize and Wheat Improvement Center (CIMMYT) announced a <a href="http://www.basf.com/group/pressrelease/P-11-299" target="_blank">four-year project</a> to reduce crop loss due to the parasitic Striga weed (Striga hermonthica and S. gesnerioides) from the maize and legume fields of Kenya and Nigeria. Funding for the project comes from a four-year grant from the Bill &amp; Melinda Gates Foundation to IITA to implement and evaluate four different approaches to controlling the parasitic weed. BASF is making an in-kind donation of research and development resources and is also providing technology access to its StrigAway® production system (herbicide coated seeds) to support the development and testing of one approach.(BASF, 6/6/2011)F, 6/6/2011)</p>
							<p><span class="date">30/08/2011</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Biotechnology/Related-developments/BASF-partners-with-leading-research-institutes-to-reduce-crop-loss-from-striga-weed-in-Africa">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Biotechnology/Related-developments/Universities-in-West-Africa-share-resources-for-new-biotechnology-masters-programme" title="Universities in West Africa share resources for new biotechnology masters programme" alt="link">Universities in West Africa share resources for new biotechnology masters programme</a></h2>

	
					<p>







 




  
  

	
	<a href="/var/knowledge/storage/images/media/images/61whatisbiotech/341263-1-eng-GB/61whatisbiotech.png" rel="lightbox[]">	
	  </a>
	
	
	
	
  	






	 
  





	Seven West African universities have created a masters degree in tropical biotechnologies. The universities are Cheikh Anta Diop of Dakar in Senegal; Abobo-Adjamey of Abidjan in Côte d'Ivoire; Abomey-Calavi of Cotonou in Benin; Abdou Moumouni of Niamey in Niger; Bamako in Mali; Nouakchott in Mauritania; and Ouagadougou in Burkina Faso. The countries are all members of the Economic Community of West African States, ECOWAS. The programme is to address the limited capacity of present human resources in this branch of agricultural research. The course will be given online to ensure quality and to make it accessible to all students in the region. From 2012 on, the masters will offer two specialisations, in plant biotechnology and in agricultural and environmental biotechnology. (<a href="http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=20110701161308293" target="_blank">University World News</a>, 3/7/2011)</p>
							<p><span class="date">23/07/2011</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Biotechnology/Related-developments/Universities-in-West-Africa-share-resources-for-new-biotechnology-masters-programme">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
