						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Biotechnology/Related-developments/PNG-s-NARI-releases-two-blight-resistant-potato-varieties" title="PNG’s NARI releases two blight resistant potato varieties" alt="link">PNG’s NARI releases two blight resistant potato varieties</a></h2>

	
					<p>







 




  
  

	
	<a href="/var/knowledge/storage/images/media/images/phytophtora_infestans-effects-huge/337717-1-eng-GB/Phytophtora_infestans-effects-huge.jpg" rel="lightbox[]">	
	  </a>
	
	
	
	
  	






	 
  





	Papua New Guinea’s potato industry suffers from the potato late blight (PLB, <i>Phytophthora infestans</i>). The Sequoia, PNG’s most common potato variety, is highly susceptible to PLB. After a devastating outbreak in 2003, only commercial farmers who could afford fungicides, portable sprayers and potato seeds did continue to grow the crop. However, smallholders farmers on the islands could not afford to buy the standard remedial to the blight. Especially for the farmers living at higher altitude, potato was an important cash and subsistence crop. In May 2011, PNG’s National Agricultural Research Institute released two late blight resistant potato varieties, the product of a large-scale project that start started in 2003 with the assistance of the Australian Centre for International Agricultural Research (ACIAR). Blight resistant potato seeds are now distributed to farmers, who are also offered training on integrated late blight management for existing and new potato cultivars. (<a href="http://malumnalu.blogspot.com/2011/05/breakthrough-against-potato-disease.html" target="_blank">Malum Nalu, 31/5/2011</a>)</p>
							<p><span class="date">1/07/2011</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Biotechnology/Related-developments/PNG-s-NARI-releases-two-blight-resistant-potato-varieties">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="event" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Biotechnology/Related-developments/SACAU-Policy-Conference-2011-GMOs-in-Agricultural-development-Perspectives-of-farmers-in-Southern-Africa" title="SACAU Policy Conference 2011: GMOs in Agricultural development - Perspectives of farmers in Southern Africa" alt="event">SACAU Policy Conference 2011: GMOs in Agricultural development - Perspectives of farmers in Southern Africa</a></h2>

	
	
					<p>







 




  
  

	
	<a href="/var/knowledge/storage/images/media/images/sacau-logo/322816-1-eng-GB/sacau-logo.jpg" rel="lightbox[]">	
	  </a>
	
	
	
	
  	






	 
  





	The Southern African Confederation of Agricultural Unions (SACAU) will be holding its Annual Policy Conference. The theme will be of the conference will be on &quot;<b>GMOs in Agricultural development - perspectives of farmers in Southern Africa</b>&quot;. The Conference will be held on 16 - 17 May, in South Africa.Various papers will be presented and discussed at the conference, and the topics covered will include: 


GMOs in the context of Biotech in agriculture 

pro-GMO perspectives 

anti-GMO perspectives 

market access/trade issues 

consumer perspectives 

existing policy frameworks 

recent technological advances


Farmers in Southern Africa is expected to come up with key messages and position statements in response to the issues raised during the Conference.The venue for the Conference is: <b>Riviera on Vaal</b>, <b>Vereeniging</b>, <b>South Africa</b>. <a href="http://www.rivieraonvaal.co.za" target="_blank">www.rivieraonvaal.co.za</a> Tthe dates are: <b>16 and 17 May 2011</b>.Kindly contact Dorita Swart at info@sacau.org for further details should you be interested to attend this Policy Conference .</p>
					<p><span class="date">Monday 16 May 2011 - Tuesday 17 May 2011</p><div class="cnt">
	<a class="event" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Biotechnology/Related-developments/SACAU-Policy-Conference-2011-GMOs-in-Agricultural-development-Perspectives-of-farmers-in-Southern-Africa">Read more...</a>
